In C#, you can set a default value for a property by using an initializer or by setting the default value in the property's getter method. Here's an example:

```csharp
public string MyProperty { get; set; } = "Default value";
```

In this example, the property `MyProperty` is initialized with the default value of `"Default value"`. You can replace `"Default value"` with any other value that suits your requirement.

Alternatively, if you're using an older version of C# that doesn't support property initializers, you can set the default value in the property's getter method:

```csharp
private string myProperty = "Default value";

public string MyProperty 
{
    get { return myProperty; }
    set { myProperty = value; }
}
```

In this case, the property `MyProperty` has a default value of `"Default value"`.

Apologies for the confusion. If you want to set a default value for a property in C# without using property initializer syntax, you can initialize the property in the constructor of the class. Here's an example:

```csharp
public class MyClass
{
    public string MyProperty { get; set; }

    public MyClass()
    {
        MyProperty = "Default value";
    }
}
```

In this example, the `MyProperty` property is initialized with the default value of `"Default value"` in the constructor of the `MyClass` class. Whenever an instance of `MyClass` is created, `MyProperty` will have the default value unless it is explicitly set to a different value.

If you are referring to clearing the console screen in C#, you can use the `Console.Clear()` method. Here's an example:

```csharp
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("This is some text.");
        Console.WriteLine("Press any key to clear the screen.");
        Console.ReadKey();
        Console.Clear();
        Console.WriteLine("The screen has been cleared.");
    }
}
```

In this example, the `Console.Clear()` method is called after a key is pressed. It clears the console screen, and you can see the message "The screen has been cleared" printed after the screen is cleared.

Note that `Console.Clear()` will only work in console applications, and not in other types of applications like Windows Forms or WPF applications.
